modules.description: Calculates centroid coordinates from a structured data type, and retrieves the minimum and maximum coordinate pairs. It operates on a custom type that represents spatial data. Used to analyze and summarize spatial distributions within internal processing pipelines.

Calculates centroid coordinates from a structured data type, and retrieves the minimum and maximum coordinate pairs. Operates on a custom type containing lists of float pairs. Used to analyze spatial data points within internal processing pipelines.

Calculates centroid coordinates from a structured spatial data type, while also extracting minimum and maximum coordinate pairs to summarize spatial distributions. It processes a custom spatial data structure, supporting operations like centroid computation and range retrieval. This enables precise spatial analysis within data processing workflows. For example, it can determine the central point of a dataset or identify the bounding box of spatial points.

Calculates centroid coordinates and identifies min/max coordinate pairs from a custom type representing lists of float pairs, enabling spatial analysis. It supports operations that process and aggregate geometric data within structured pipelines. Users can compute average positions and extract boundary values from datasets. This facilitates tasks like clustering, bounding box generation, and spatial normalization.

Calculates centroid coordinates from a structured data type, and retrieves the minimum and maximum coordinate pairs. Operates on a custom type containing lists of float pairs. Used internally to analyze spatial data points in computational geometry tasks.

Computes approximate percentiles and quantiles from a stream of real numbers using the T-Digest algorithm. It maintains a compressed representation of the data using a tree-like structure with weighted nodes. Ideal for real-time analytics on large datasets where exact precision is not required but accuracy in tail regions is critical.

Calculates centroid coordinates and extracts minimum and maximum coordinate pairs from structured data types containing lists of float pairs, enabling spatial analysis. It supports operations such as averaging positions, determining bounding boxes, and aggregating geometric data for computational geometry tasks. Users can compute central points of datasets or identify spatial boundaries for clustering and normalization. Examples include generating bounding boxes for spatial datasets or calculating average locations in geometric pipelines.
